Lessons Learned ‚Äì TDE Implementation
1. Encryption / Decryption Throughput Slower Than Expected

Actual encryption and decryption speeds were lower than initial estimates.

This extended the overall completion timeline, especially for larger databases.

Improvement Action:

Perform throughput benchmarking in non-production environments.

Adjust implementation timelines based on realistic performance baselines.

Management Takeaway:

Timelines should be based on measured performance, not assumptions.

2. Validation and Synchronization Took Longer Than Planned

Post-encryption validation and synchronization exceeded the planned maintenance window.

Testing was largely sequential, which increased total duration.

Improvement Action:

Enable testing-on-the-go, with the testing team validating objects and data as encryption progresses.

Run validation tasks in parallel where possible.

Management Takeaway:

Parallel testing significantly reduces overall project duration.

3. Limited Real-Time Visibility Into Encryption Progress

Native SQL Server monitoring provided limited real-time insights.

Progress tracking required manual checks and estimation.

Improvement Action:

Integrate monitoring tools such as Datadog to track:

Encryption progress

CPU and I/O impact

Long-running background tasks

Management Takeaway:

Enhanced observability improves decision-making and confidence during critical changes.

Summary for Leadership

No failures occurred, but timeline accuracy and visibility can be improved.

Future implementations will benefit from:

Performance baselining

Parallel testing

Enhanced real-time monitoring

Overall Result: Lessons learned will improve predictability, reduce maintenance windows, and increase operational transparency in future TDE deployments.

